## Async Graph Analytics — background compute + persisted last result

Context: The Knowledge Graph Analytics computation (NetworkX centrality /
structure) ran synchronously, blocking the browser until it finished, and the
Domain Validation cockpit even re-ran a full compute on every page load. On
large graphs this is slow and wasteful. Made the analysis asynchronous (a
background `TaskManager` task), persisted **only the last** result per
`(domain, version)` in a new Lakebase `graph_analytics` cache, and switched the
Analytics page and the cockpit to render from that stored result.

Key design decisions:
- One row per `(domain_id, version)`, UPSERTed on every successful recompute —
  literally "only the last one persists". The full `compute_graph_metrics`
  payload is stored in a `result` JSONB column so the page tabs and the AI
  Interpret agent rebuild everything from storage; `stats` / `top_pagerank` are
  denormalised for the cheap cockpit summary read.
- Reused the existing KG-build async convention: `POST /dtwin/metrics/compute`
  now returns a `task_id`, the frontend polls `/tasks/{id}` via the global
  `waitForTask()` then reads `/dtwin/metrics/latest`. Mirrored the `build_runs`
  store pattern (lazy `_ensure_*` self-heal DDL, best-effort writes).
- Failures leave the previous good cached row intact (the error surfaces via the
  global task tracker, not the cache).

