## In-app registry permission grants (Initialize + Repair permissions button)

Context: The Lakebase registry-schema GRANTs (CAN_USE on the project,
USAGE/CREATE/DML on the schema, UC catalog ALL_PRIVILEGES) were only available
via scripts/bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh, which needs psql at deploy time. The
app connects to Lakebase as its own service principal and OWNS the registry
schema after Initialize, so it can run these GRANTs itself — exactly as the
in-app graph-DB provisioner already does for the graph schema. Surfaced the
same capability for the registry: Initialize now auto-applies the grants and a
new "Repair permissions" button re-applies them idempotently. This removes the
psql dependency for the everyday registry schema grants (control-plane CAN_USE/
UC grants stay best-effort in-app, mirroring the bash script).

Changes:

1. src/back/core/databricks/lakebase_grants.py (new)
   - Extracted the grant primitives into one reusable, TaskManager-free module:
     resolve_app_service_principals, grant_can_use_on_project,
     grant_schema_privileges, grant_uc_catalog. Each returns (granted, warnings);
     control-plane grants are best-effort. Single source of truth for the GRANT
     SQL/API previously inlined in the provisioner.
2. src/back/core/graphdb/lakebase/provisioner.py
   - Refactored _step_grant_can_use / _step_grant_schema / _step_grant_uc and
     _resolve_service_principals to delegate to lakebase_grants (removed the
     duplicated GRANT bodies and the now-unused _app_service_principal). Behaviour
     unchanged — the graph-DB provision flow still applies the same grants.
3. src/back/objects/registry/store/lakebase/store.py
   - Added LakebaseRegistryStore.grant_app_permissions(app_names, uc_catalog):
     in-app port of bootstrap-lakebase-perms.sh for the registry schema. Resolves
     each app SP via the Apps API, grants CAN_USE on the project (best-effort),
     USAGE/DML on the schema (the SP owns it), and UC ALL_PRIVILEGES when set.
     Returns {success, granted, warnings, error, schema, apps}.
4. src/back/objects/domain/SettingsService.py
   - Added _registry_grant_app_names (running app + MCP app), the shared sync
     core _grant_registry_permissions, and the async
     grant_registry_permissions_result. Hooked _grant_registry_permissions into
     initialize_registry_result so Initialize self-applies the grants and returns
     them under a new "permissions" key (best-effort, never fatal to Initialize).
5. src/api/routers/internal/settings.py
   - New admin-only route POST /settings/registry/grant-permissions →
     grant_registry_permissions_result. initialize_registry now runs via
     run_blocking (the auto-grant does blocking I/O) and documents the new
     permissions key.
6. src/front/templates/partials/registry/_registry_configuration.html
   - Added the admin-gated "Repair permissions" button (Lakebase Connection
     panel), a "Permission Grants" results panel, the _renderGrantResult renderer
     (exposed as window._obRenderRegistryGrants), and the button click handler.
7. src/front/static/registry/js/registry.js
   - Initialize handler now renders the returned permissions summary and warns
     when any grant produced a warning.
8. docs/deployment.md
   - Documented the in-app alternative (no psql) in Step 5b and the Initialize /
     Repair permissions behaviour in Step 8.
9. docs/sphinx/api/app.core.databricks.rst
   - Added the lakebase_grants automodule entry.

